sentence: As Q1 earnings season continues , more and more companies are starting to post their earnings results.
On Tuesday, four consumer products companies reported their quarterly earnings results before the bell.
Let's take a look.
BP, one of the world's largest petroleum and petrochemicals group, reported mixed Q1 results .
Adjusted earnings per share of $0.17 (excluding non-recurring items) beat the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $-0.26 per share.
Total revenues came in at $39.166 billion, reflecting a sharp year-over-year decline from the year-ago level of $56.243 billion.
BP expects second-quarter 2016 production to be lower than the first quarter, reflecting PSA entitlement impact, seasonal turnaround and maintenance activity.
The luxury retailer reported better than expected third quarter fiscal 2016 earnings .
Adjusted earnings per share came in at $0.44, topping the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $0.41 per share and marking Coach's ninth consecutive quarterly earnings beat.
Net sales came in at $1.033 billion, edging past the Zacks Consensus Estimate pf $1.024 billion.
Guidance for 2016 remains intact.
Office supplies company Office Depot reported disappointing Q1 results .
Earnings per share came in at $0.10 (excludes $0.02 from non-recurring items), missing the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $0.13 per share.
Revenues of $3.54 billion lagged behind our consensus estimate of $3.619 billion.
Office Depot says its weaker than expected results stemmed from the extended regulatory process ahead of its merger with Staples, negatively impacting its business levels.
The consumer goods giant reported strong Q3 earnings results .
Adjusted earnings per share of $0.86 beat the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $0.81 but declined 3% on a year-over-year basis.
Revenues came in at $15.73 billion, topping our consensus estimate by 0.2% after missing the same for the last eight quarters.
Despite beats on its top and bottom lines, P&G has narrowed its fiscal 2016 earnings guidance.
Including all of this morning's results, we now have Q1 results from 166 S&P 500 members that combined account for 42.6% of the index's total market capitalization.
Total earnings for these companies are down -7.6% from the same period last year on -1.3% lower revenues, with 75.3% beating EPS estimates and 54.2% coming ahead of revenue estimates.
Relative to other recent periods, this is weak earnings and revenue growth from these 166 index members.
But positive surprises are more numerous relative to other recent periods, both for earnings as well as revenues.
The favorable trend in surprises could be interpreted to mean that estimates may have fallen too much in the run up to the start of the Q1 earnings season.

Looking at Q1 as a whole, combining the actual results from the 166 S&P 500 members that have reported with estimates for the still-to-come 334 index members, total earnings are expected to be down -9.4% on -1.2% lower revenues - the 4th quarter in a row of earnings declines for the index.
Estimates for 2016 Q2 have started to come down, with total earnings for the S&P 500 index now expected to be down -5.2% from the same period last year.
